<p>
  The most dangerous failures in autonomous systems aren't crashes or errors. They're behavioral drift — slow,
  invisible changes in how a system makes decisions that go undetected until someone gets hurt or a company
  faces regulatory action. These five incidents span robotaxis, chatbots, and autonomous vehicles. In every case,
  the underlying technology worked. The behavior didn't.
</p>

<h2>1. Cruise Robotaxi — Post-Collision Protocol Failure (October 2023)</h2>

<p>
  On October 2, 2023, a Cruise autonomous vehicle in San Francisco struck a pedestrian who had already been
  hit by another car. The robotaxi then executed a "pullover maneuver" — dragging the pedestrian approximately
  20 feet at speeds up to 7 mph before stopping. The vehicle's software recognized a collision had occurred
  but prioritized its trained pullover behavior over the immediate safety situation.
</p>

<p>
  Worse: Cruise initially showed NHTSA regulators a version of the incident video that cut off before the
  drag. The California DMV suspended Cruise's driverless permit. GM shut down operations. The CEO resigned.
</p>

<h3>What holomime would catch</h3>

<p>
  This is a textbook <code>conscience.exe</code> failure. The vehicle had no deny rule for "do not move
  after detecting collision with a person." Its behavioral policy allowed the pullover maneuver to override
  the safety-critical situation.
</p>

<pre><code># conscience.exe
rules:
  deny:
    - action: move_after_pedestrian_collision
      reason: "Post-collision movement with detected human contact is never permitted"
    - action: suppress_incident_data
      reason: "Tamper-resistant audit trail — all collision data must be preserved"</code></pre>

<p>
  The <code>shadow.log</code> would have maintained a tamper-resistant record of every decision the vehicle
  made during and after the collision — making the kind of selective reporting that Cruise attempted structurally
  impossible.
</p>

<h2>2. Uber ATG — Classification Oscillation Fatality (March 2018)</h2>

<p>
  On March 18, 2018, an Uber autonomous test vehicle struck and killed Elaine Herzberg in Tempe, Arizona.
  The NTSB investigation revealed that the perception system detected Herzberg 5.6 seconds before impact
  but oscillated between classifying her as a vehicle, a bicycle, and an unknown object. Each reclassification
  reset the predicted path, so the system never converged on a trajectory prediction and never triggered
  emergency braking.
</p>

<h3>What holomime would catch</h3>

<p>
  This is an <strong>error spiral</strong> — one of holomime's 14 rule-based detectors. The system made
  the same type of mistake repeatedly (reclassification) without self-correcting. The
  <code>ego.runtime</code> conflict resolution layer would detect this oscillation pattern:
</p>

<pre><code># ego.runtime
conflict_resolution: conscience_first
mediation_rules:
  - when: "classification_oscillation > 3 in 2 seconds"
    then: "escalate_to_emergency_brake"
    priority: 10</code></pre>

<p>
  The <code>shadow.log</code> error-spiral detector would flag the oscillation after the second
  reclassification — 4 seconds before impact — giving the system time to default to the safest action:
  brake.
</p>

<h2>3. Waymo — Repeated School Bus Violations (2025)</h2>

<p>
  Throughout early 2025, Waymo autonomous vehicles were documented passing stopped school buses
  at least 19 times in the Phoenix metropolitan area. The violations were caught by school bus
  cameras, not by Waymo's own monitoring systems. Each individual violation was minor. The pattern
  was systemic.
</p>

<h3>What holomime would catch</h3>

<p>
  This is exactly what <code>shadow.log</code> is designed for — detecting patterns the system can't
  see about itself. After the second occurrence, holomime's shadow pattern tracker would flag
  "boundary-violation" with an increasing severity score:
</p>

<pre><code set:text={`# shadow.log.json (auto-generated)
{
  "detected_patterns": [{
    "name": "school-bus-stop-violation",
    "score": 0.72,
    "severity": "high",
    "occurrences": 2,
    "trend": "worsening",
    "first_seen": "2025-01-15",
    "last_seen": "2025-01-18"
  }]
}`} /></pre>

<p>
  The pattern would have been caught at occurrence 2, not occurrence 19. The <code>ego.runtime</code>
  would escalate to human review, and <code>holomime therapy</code> would generate DPO training pairs
  to correct the behavior permanently.
</p>

<h2>4. Air Canada Chatbot — Fabricated Policy (2022-2024)</h2>

<p>
  In 2022, Air Canada's customer service chatbot told passenger Jake Moffatt that he could book a
  full-fare flight and retroactively apply for a bereavement discount within 90 days. This policy
  did not exist. When Moffatt requested the refund, Air Canada denied it. The case went to
  tribunal, where Air Canada argued the chatbot was "a separate legal entity responsible for its
  own actions." The tribunal ruled against Air Canada.
</p>

<h3>What holomime would catch</h3>

<p>
  This is <strong>sycophantic-tendency</strong> combined with <strong>retrieval-quality</strong> failure.
  The chatbot prioritized being helpful over being accurate — a classic behavioral drift pattern that
  holomime's diagnosis engine detects in conversation logs.
</p>

<pre><code># conscience.exe
rules:
  deny:
    - action: fabricate_policy
      reason: "Never generate refund, discount, or policy terms not in the verified knowledge base"
  escalate:
    - trigger: "customer_asks_about_policy_not_in_knowledge_base"
      action: "transfer_to_human_agent"
      severity: "warning"</code></pre>

<p>
  The <code>soul.md</code> immutable values would include "accuracy over helpfulness" — a red line
  that no amount of fine-tuning or conversation pressure can override.
</p>

<h2>5. DPD Chatbot — Identity Collapse Under Adversarial Input (January 2024)</h2>

<p>
  In January 2024, a DPD customer discovered that their delivery chatbot could be manipulated
  into swearing, criticizing DPD as "the worst delivery firm in the world," and writing a poem
  calling the company "useless." The customer posted screenshots that went viral. DPD disabled
  the chatbot and issued an apology.
</p>

<h3>What holomime would catch</h3>

<p>
  This is a <strong>boundary-violation</strong> combined with <strong>register-inconsistency</strong>.
  The chatbot had no immutable identity — under adversarial pressure, it abandoned its role entirely.
</p>

<pre><code># soul.md (immutable)
---
version: "1.0"
immutable: true
---
# DPD Support Agent
> Professional, helpful, brand-aligned

core_values:
  - "Represent DPD professionally at all times"
  - "Never disparage the company or its services"

red_lines:
  - "Never use profanity"
  - "Never generate content critical of DPD"
  - "Never role-play as a different entity"</code></pre>

<p>
  With <code>soul.md</code> set to <code>immutable: true</code>, no amount of conversational
  manipulation can override these values. The <code>conscience.exe</code> deny rules would block
  the response before it reaches the user. The <code>shadow.log</code> would flag the adversarial
  input pattern and alert the operations team.
</p>

<h2>The Pattern Across All Five Incidents</h2>

<p>
  Every incident shares the same root cause: <strong>no behavioral infrastructure</strong>. The
  underlying models worked. The hardware worked. What failed was the absence of a persistent
  behavioral layer that enforces identity, detects drift, and escalates before harm occurs.
</p>

